# Origin & Character
# Zambra: Moorish-rooted flamenco dance from Granada
# Originally performed by Gitanos (Spanish Roma) in Sacromonte caves
# Character: Sensual, hypnotic, Middle Eastern influence
# Often features dramatic arm movements and hip sways

# Compas Reference
# Time signature: 4/4 or 2/4
# Feel: Swaying, undulating, trance-like
# Less percussive than Tangos, more flowing
# Accents often on 1 and 3, but with fluid subdivision

# Scale Reference
# C# Phrygian Dominant (5th mode of F# harmonic minor)
# C#-D-E#-F#-G#-A-B
# The raised 3rd (E# = F natural) gives exotic Moorish color
# Often uses augmented 2nd interval (D to E#) for Middle Eastern flavor

# Zone-Tritone Connection
# bII -> I (D -> C#) zone-crossing resolution
# C#=1(Z2), D=2(Z1) -- ZONE CROSS
# Tritone: E#-B (3rd & b7 of C#7) resolves to F# minor (parent)
# The Moorish flavor comes from emphasizing the augmented 2nd

# Harmony Reference
# Key: C# Phrygian Dominant (C#-D-E#-F#-G#-A-B)
# Typical chords: C#(I) - D(bII) - F#m(iv) - C#(I)
# The D major chord (bII) has strong gravitational pull
# Augmented 2nd (D to E#) = signature Moorish interval

# Technique Reference
# Right-hand: Flowing arpeggios, tremolo, soft rasgueados
# Left-hand: Ornaments emphasizing the augmented 2nd
# Character: Hypnotic, swaying, less aggressive than other palos

